content.text:
Here’s `src/env.ts` in plain terms.

## Imports
```1:3:apps/api/src/env.ts
import { createEnv } from "@t3-oss/env-core";
import type { PinoLogger } from "hono-pino";
import { z } from "zod";
```

`zod` defines validation rules. `createEnv` runs those rules and returns a typed env object. `PinoLogger` is just for Hono’s `Variables` type at the bottom.

## `DATABASE_URL` Rule
```5:10:apps/api/src/env.ts
export const databaseUrlSchema = z
  .url()
  .refine(
    (url) => url.startsWith("postgres://") || url.startsWith("postgresql://"),
    "DATABASE_URL must be a Postgres connection string.",
  );
```

This says `DATABASE_URL` must be a valid URL, and it must specifically be a Postgres URL. So `https://example.com` is a valid URL, but not a valid database URL for us.

This is exported because `drizzle.config.ts` reuses it for Node-side validation.

## Rate Limit Binding Check
```12:19:apps/api/src/env.ts
function isRateLimitBinding(value: unknown): value is RateLimit {
  return (
    typeof value === "object" &&
    value !== null &&
    "limit" in value &&
    typeof (value as { limit?: unknown }).limit === "function"
  );
}
```

`API_RATE_LIMITER` is not a string env var. It is a Cloudflare binding object. Zod cannot know Cloudflare’s `RateLimit` type at runtime, so this checks for the one capability we need: a `.limit()` function.

The `value is RateLimit` part is TypeScript narrowing.

## Main Env Schema
```21:33:apps/api/src/env.ts
export const serverEnvSchema = {
  DATABASE_URL: databaseUrlSchema,
  LOGTAIL_SOURCE_TOKEN: z.string().min(1),
  LOGTAIL_ENDPOINT: z.url().optional(),
  CORS_ORIGIN: z.string().min(1).default("http://localhost:3209"),
  ENVIRONMENT: z
    .enum(["development", "staging", "production", "test"])
    .default("development"),
  LOG_LEVEL: z
    .enum(["fatal", "error", "warn", "info", "debug", "trace", "silent"])
    .default("info"),
  API_RATE_LIMITER: z.custom<RateLimit>(isRateLimitBinding).optional(),
} as const;
```

This is the core of the file. It defines every env binding the app is allowed to use after validation.

Required:
- `DATABASE_URL`
- `LOGTAIL_SOURCE_TOKEN`

Optional:
- `LOGTAIL_ENDPOINT`
- `API_RATE_LIMITER`

Defaulted:
- `CORS_ORIGIN`
- `ENVIRONMENT`
- `LOG_LEVEL`

So after `parseBindings()`, code can treat defaults as present.

## Why We Widen Wrangler Types
```35:39:apps/api/src/env.ts
type WidenStringValues<T> = {
  [K in keyof T]: T[K] extends string ? string : T[K];
};

type GeneratedRuntimeBindings = WidenStringValues<Env>;
```

Wrangler generates `ENVIRONMENT: "development"` because `wrangler.jsonc` currently has that exact value.

But tests need `ENVIRONMENT: "test"`, and deployments may use `"staging"` or `"production"`. So this converts string literal types like `"development"` into plain `string` before validation.

Wrangler still tells us which keys exist. Zod decides which values are valid.

## Runtime Input Type
```40:52:apps/api/src/env.ts
type OptionalRuntimeBindingKey =
  | "API_RATE_LIMITER"
  | "CORS_ORIGIN"
  | "ENVIRONMENT"
  | "LOG_LEVEL";

export type RuntimeBindings = Omit<
  GeneratedRuntimeBindings,
  OptionalRuntimeBindingKey
> &
  Partial<Pick<GeneratedRuntimeBindings, OptionalRuntimeBindingKey>> & {
    LOGTAIL_ENDPOINT?: string;
  };
```

This type describes what `parseBindings()` accepts.

It starts from Wrangler’s generated `Env`, but makes a few keys optional:
- `API_RATE_LIMITER`, so tests can run without Cloudflare’s binding object.
- `CORS_ORIGIN`, `ENVIRONMENT`, `LOG_LEVEL`, because Zod provides defaults.
- `LOGTAIL_ENDPOINT`, because it is optional and not currently generated by Wrangler.

## Shape Required by T3 Env
```54:69:apps/api/src/env.ts
type ServerEnvKey = keyof typeof serverEnvSchema;
type T3RuntimeEnv = Record<ServerEnvKey, string | boolean | number | undefined>;

function createRuntimeEnv(runtimeEnv: RuntimeBindings): T3RuntimeEnv {
  return {
    DATABASE_URL: runtimeEnv.DATABASE_URL,
    LOGTAIL_SOURCE_TOKEN: runtimeEnv.LOGTAIL_SOURCE_TOKEN,
    LOGTAIL_ENDPOINT: runtimeEnv.LOGTAIL_ENDPOINT,
    CORS_ORIGIN: runtimeEnv.CORS_ORIGIN,
    ENVIRONMENT: runtimeEnv.ENVIRONMENT,
    LOG_LEVEL: runtimeEnv.LOG_LEVEL,
    API_RATE_LIMITER: runtimeEnv.API_RATE_LIMITER as unknown as
      | string
      | undefined,
  };
}
```

T3 Env’s `runtimeEnvStrict` wants a record of schema keys to primitive env-like values. Cloudflare gives us mostly strings, but `API_RATE_LIMITER` is an object.

The cast on `API_RATE_LIMITER` is the awkward bit: it gets the binding through T3’s expected input shape so Zod’s `z.custom<RateLimit>()` can validate it. Runtime-wise, the object is still the same object.

## The Actual Parser
```71:78:apps/api/src/env.ts
export function parseBindings(runtimeEnv: RuntimeBindings) {
  return createEnv({
    server: serverEnvSchema,
    runtimeEnvStrict: createRuntimeEnv(runtimeEnv),
    emptyStringAsUndefined: true,
    isServer: true,
  });
}
```

This is the function the app calls at the Worker boundary.

It:
- validates env values,
- applies defaults,
- rejects invalid/missing required values,
- returns a strongly typed object.

`emptyStringAsUndefined: true` means `LOGTAIL_ENDPOINT=""` behaves like missing instead of invalid empty URL.

## App Env Type
```80:95:apps/api/src/env.ts
export type Bindings = ReturnType<typeof parseBindings>;

type AssertTrue<T extends true> = T;
type WranglerEnvCoverage = Exclude<keyof Env, keyof Bindings> extends never
  ? true
  : ["Missing in Zod schema:", Exclude<keyof Env, keyof Bindings>];

export type EnsureEnvCoverage = AssertTrue<WranglerEnvCoverage>;

export type AppEnv = {
  Bindings: Bindings;
  Variables: {
    requestId: string;
    logger: PinoLogger;
  };
};
```

`Bindings` is now inferred from Zod/T3, not manually written.

The coverage check makes TypeScript fail if Wrangler generates a binding that is not represented in the validated `Bindings` type.

`AppEnv` is the Hono environment type. This is what lets route handlers use `c.env.DATABASE_URL`, `c.env.LOG_LEVEL`, etc. with validated types.

In one sentence: Wrangler says what Cloudflare provides, `parseBindings()` validates and normalizes it, and `Bindings` becomes the app’s trusted env type.
